You instruct the mock ObjectMapper to throw, but the code under test doesn&#39;t use that mock mapper; it uses its own mapper which it constructs by calling the ObjectMapper constructor.

It is necessary to inject the mock mapper into the code, either by passing it as an additional parameter, or through dependency injection. In general, avoid new-ing up dependencies. I&#39;m not sure what dependency injection framework you&#39;re using, if any. Where I work, we would do something like the following with Spring Boot:

    // in a configuration class somewhere in the project
    @Configuration
    public class SpiderConfig {
        @Bean
        public ObjectMapper objectMapper() {
            ObjectMapper mapper = new ObjectMapper();
            mapper.setDateFormat(new ISO8601DateFormat());
            // any other configuration of standard project mapper
            return mapper;
        }
    }

    // in the service which uses the ObjectMapper
    @Service
    public class SpiderService {
        @Autowired
        private ObjectMapper mapper;

        // etc.
    }

    // in the unit test
    @Mock
    private ObjectMapper mapper;

    @InjectMocks
    private SpiderService service;

    @Test
    public void testGetMyObjectJPE() throws JsonProcessingException {
        when(mapper.writeValueAsString(...)...

When the service runs normally, a real ObjectMapper will be injected into the autowired field, but when the unit test runs it will inject a mock ObjectMapper.

Of course, if you are not using Spring Boot, there are other ways to inject the mock. The simplest, using no DI framework, would be to provide a setter for the mapper field, or use reflection in the unit test to set the mapper.

Additionally, this code:

    Mockito.when(mapper.writeValueAsString(myObject.getCreateTime())).thenThrow(JsonProcessingException.class);
    Mockito.when(myObject.getCreateTime()).thenReturn(testCreateDate);

Should probably be:

    Mockito.when(mapper.writeValueAsString(testCreateDate)).thenThrow(JsonProcessingException.class);
    Mockito.when(myObject.getCreateTime()).thenReturn(testCreateDate);

In the first case, you are mocking the `writeValueAsString` method to throw whenever it is called with whatever your object&#39;s `getCreateTime` method will return, but it is the actual return value after you&#39;ve just created the object, *not* the `testCreateDate` that you are *about* to mock the spy to return.

When the actual call occurs in your code under test, it passes the `testCreateDate` which does not match the value you&#39;ve told it to throw for, so the mock ObjectMapper probably just returns `null` or `&quot;&quot;` or something like that. However, without the mock mapper being injected, this won&#39;t matter and if you&#39;ve replaced the value with `any()` then the specific value is not relevant.

(By the way, I hope you know that `java.util.Date` is considered horribly obsolete and broken these days, and should only be used by legacy code.)

